$ and $\\sim 0.9\\ M_\\odot$ located at a distance\n$\\sim 3$ kpc. In addition, we are able to constrain the complete orbital\nparameters of the lens thanks to the precise measurement of the microlens\nparallax derived from the joint analysis. In contrast to the binary event\nOGLE-2014-BLG-1050, which was also observed by {\\it Spitzer}, we find that the\ninterpretation of OGLE-2015-BLG-0479 does not suffer from the degeneracy\nbetween $(\\pm,\\pm)$ and $(\\pm,\\mp)$ solutions, confirming that the four-fold\nparallax degeneracy in single-lens events collapses into the two-fold\ndegeneracy for the general case of binary-lens events. The location of the\nblend in the color-magnitude diagram is consistent with the lens properties,\nsuggesting that the blend is the lens itself. The blend is bright enough for\nspectroscopy and thus this possibility can be checked from future follow-up\nobservations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 30 Jun 2016 06:06:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-09-07"}
