{"id":"1606.09372","submitter":"John Martin","authors":"F. Damanet and J. Martin","title":"Competition between finite-size effects and dipole-dipole interactions\n  in few-atom systems","comments":"11 pages, 11 figures","journal-ref":"J. Phys. B: At. Mol. Opt. Phys. 49, 225501 (2016)","doi":"10.1088/0953-4075/49/22/225501","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we study the competition between finite-size effects (i.e.\ndiscernibility of particles) and dipole-dipole interactions in few-atom systems\ncoupled to the electromagnetic field in vacuum. We consider two hallmarks of\ncooperative effects, superradiance and subradiance, and compute for each the\nrate of energy radiated by the atoms and the coherence of the atomic state\nduring the time evolution. We adopt a statistical approach in order to extract\nthe typical behavior of the atomic dynamics and average over random atomic\ndistributions in spherical containers with prescribed $k_0R$ with $k_0$ the\nradiation wavenumber and $R$ the average interatomic distance. Our approach\nallows us to highlight the tradeoff between finite-size effects and\ndipole-dipole interactions in superradiance/subradiance. In particular, we show\nthe existence of an optimal value of $k_0R$ for which the superradiant\nintensity and coherence pulses are the less affected by dephasing effects\ninduced by dipole-dipole interactions and finite-size effects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 30 Jun 2016 07:29:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 9 Oct 2017 12:14:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-10-10"}
